data.content:
xUnit doesn't use setup/teardown attributes. Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + `IDisposable` |

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

// Test class uses constructor/Dispose for per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();    // SetUp
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();               // TearDown
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- **Per-test**: xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` naturally replace `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`
- **Per-class**: `IClassFixture<T>` shares one fixture instance across all tests in the class — the fixture's constructor/`Dispose` replace `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`
- **Assertions**: `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` → `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)`
